    <section id="sexagenary-cycle">
      <h2>The Sexagenary Cycle (<span class="chinese-char">六十干支</span>)</h2>
      <p>The sexagenary cycle creates 60 unique combinations by pairing Heavenly Stems with Earthly Branches. Because Yang stems only pair with Yang branches and Yin with Yin, the result is 60 (not 120) combinations. The cycle repeats every 60 years, months, days, and double-hours, providing a multi-layered temporal framework.</p>
      <p>The first combination is Jiǎzǐ (<span class="chinese-char">甲子</span>, Yang Wood Rat). The cycle proceeds: Yǐchǒu, Bǐngyín, Dīngmǎo... until reaching the 60th combination, Guǐhài (<span class="chinese-char">癸亥</span>, Yin Water Pig), before restarting.</p>
      <p>This 60-year cycle is the basis of the <a href="/bazi/">BaZi</a> system and determines the precise elemental character of each year. For example, 2026 is Bǐngwǔ (<span class="chinese-char">丙午</span>) &mdash; Yang Fire Horse &mdash; the 43rd combination in the current cycle.</p>
    </section>

    <section id="lunisolar">
      <h2>Lunisolar Mechanics</h2>
      <p>Months follow lunar phases: each begins on a new moon and lasts 29 or 30 days (averaging 29.53 days). Twelve lunar months total roughly 354 days &mdash; about 11 days short of the solar year. To prevent the calendar from drifting through the seasons, <strong>intercalary months</strong> (<span class="chinese-char">閏月</span>, rùnyuè) are inserted approximately every three years (seven times in nineteen years, following the Metonic cycle).</p>
      <p>The solar component is tracked through the <strong>24 Solar Terms</strong> (<span class="chinese-char">節氣</span>, jiéqì), which divide the sun's annual path into 24 equal segments of roughly 15 days each. Solar Terms determine which month receives an intercalary insertion and anchor the calendar to the agricultural seasons.</p>
    </section>

